  "text": "The Kafka consumer API migration analysis reveals the transition from synchronous to asynchronous consumer implementations, with two parallel implementations coexisting for compatibility.\n\n## New KafkaConsumer API Structure\nThe primary public API is `KafkaConsumer` (sg-evals/kafka--0753c489:clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/KafkaConsumer.java), which acts as a facade delegating to internal implementations through the `ConsumerDelegate` interface (sg-evals/kafka--0753c489:clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/ConsumerDelegate.java). This interface extends the `Consumer` contract (sg-evals/kafka--0753c489:clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/Consumer.java), which defines offset management methods: `commitSync()`, `commitAsync()`, `position()`, `seek()`, and `committed()`.\n\n## Implementation Strategies\n\n### Classic Implementation (Pre-KIP 848)\nThe `ClassicKafkaConsumer` (sg-evals/kafka--0753c489:clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/ClassicKafkaConsumer.java) implements the legacy group protocol with synchronous network I/O. All blocking operations (poll, metadata fetches, offset commits) execute in the application thread. It uses `ConsumerCoordinator`, `Fetcher<K,V>`, and `OffsetFetcher` components for managing group coordination and offset tracking. Offset management is direct: `commitSync()` and `commitAsync()` immediately communicate with brokers through `ConsumerNetworkClient`.\n\n### Async Implementation (KIP-848)\nThe `AsyncKafkaConsumer` (sg-evals/kafka--0753c489:clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/AsyncKafkaConsumer.java) implements the new consumer group protocol using an event-driven architecture. An `ApplicationEventHandler` processes `ApplicationEvent` instances (including `CommitEvent`, `SeekEvent`, `PollEvent`) asynchronously through a dedicated `ConsumerNetworkThread`. This decouples application thread operations from network I/O. The implementation uses `CommitRequestManager` for managing offset commits and includes `SubscriptionState` for tracking partition positions and offsets.\n\n## Key Behavioral Differences in Offset Management\n\n### Position Tracking\n- **ClassicKafkaConsumer**: Maintains position through `SubscriptionState` accessed directly during `poll()` calls. Position automatically advances as records are fetched and returned.\n- **AsyncKafkaConsumer**: Maintains position through event-based state management. `position()` calls trigger a `FetchPositionEvent` processed asynchronously through the event handler, returning the current position from `SubscriptionState`.\n\n### Offset Commits\n- **ClassicKafkaConsumer**: `commitSync(Map<TopicPartition, OffsetAndMetadata>)` at lines 735-738 and `commitAsync()` at lines 768+ execute synchronously with the application thread. The synchronous variant (line 736-737) wraps with a Duration-based timeout and calls the underlying coordinator.\n- **AsyncKafkaConsumer**: `commitSync()` at lines 1581-1583 and `commitAsync()` at lines 896-898 convert offset maps to optional and delegate to internal `commitSync/commitAsync` methods which submit `CommitEvent` instances to the `applicationEventHandler`. These methods return `CompletableFuture<Map<TopicPartition, OffsetAndMetadata>>` for async execution.\n\n### Committed Offset Retrieval\n- **ClassicKafkaConsumer** (lines 882-888): `committed()` calls fetch committed offsets synchronously from the broker using `ConsumerCoordinator`.\n- **AsyncKafkaConsumer** (lines 1043-1051): `committed()` submits an async event to fetch committed offsets, with the result obtained through `OffsetCommitMetricsManager`.\n\n## Offset Management Patterns in Consumer Integrations\n\nCamel's Kafka integration (sg-evals/camel--1006f047:components/camel-kafka/src/main/java/org/apache/camel/component/kafka/consumer/AbstractCommitManager.java) demonstrates practical offset management. The `forceCommit()` method (lines 85-95) uses `consumer.commitSync(Collections.singletonMap(partition, new OffsetAndMetadata(partitionLastOffset + 1)), Duration.ofMillis(timeout))`. This pattern shows that offsets are committed as the next offset to be consumed (lastOffset + 1), aligning with the API contract that committed offsets represent the next message to fetch.\n\n## Migration Path and Compatibility\nThe `KafkaConsumer` public API maintains backward compatibility by supporting both implementations internally. The `GroupProtocol` configuration (CLASSIC vs CONSUMER) determines which delegate is instantiated. ClassicKafkaConsumer remains for pre-KIP 848 compatibility, while AsyncKafkaConsumer represents the future direction with improved threading model and resource efficiency. Both implement identical offset management contracts through the Consumer interface, ensuring application-level transparency despite implementation differences."
}

